text: Right. And that is, so post-2011, we kind of did a deep dive and said, all right, what happened here? Did we miss the mark? Clearly, we missed the mark, but was it unexpected necessarily? And we had seen evidence of this type of behavior previously. And I'll back up. And so one of the early criticisms we got or questions we got when we were kind of pitching this product was people said, no, hedge fund managers are way too dynamic for a monthly rebound. So again, as I mentioned, we stuck to the Andrew Lowe approach of rebalancing monthly, not only because that was kind of the right periodicity, but also that's as frequently as we could get access to the dependent variable. Hedge funds only update monthly. So we couldn't run it any more frequently if we wanted to. But what we saw was that when we do those internal attributions for the fund to funds, you can infer to what degree these correlation coefficients turn over over time. And so... So not surprisingly, StatArb or Market Neutral is kind of a good example. Those are typically higher frequency strategies. And so it ends up... I mean, the big issue there, and we can talk about this later, but because their short book was so large, from a top-down statistical approach, it ended up just looking like a lot of cash. And in fact, there were hedge funds. So that was a strategy that we would say is not suitable, at least not suitable for statistical replication. Maybe you can recreate it from the bottoms up mechanically, but running a linear regression on a group of market neutral hedge funds... It's basically going to put you in a bunch of cash bond ETFs. Getting back to the long-short equity funds, a lot of people were saying, yeah, but hedge funds are way too dynamic. That's what we're paying for them for. And we were pointing to all this data saying, actually, they're not. Their value add... And again, at least in the long-short equity space, they're very good stock pickers. And collectively, there's really no stock alpha, but there is factor alpha. They are kind of timing the factors in a way that adds value relative to what's called an S&P 500. Over time, they are doing a good job collectively of kind of bundling these factors in a way that makes sense and isn't high turnover. These factor exposures, yes, they're dynamic. They migrate over time, but it's over a period of months and quarters. It's not intra-month. And so post-2011, we were looking at this. And like I said, we had the benefit of running this real-time during 2011. So obviously, the Greek euro crisis started to kick off in the back half of the year. Meanwhile, this was still at the fund of funds. And so I'm going on these manager due diligence meetings just because it's a phenomenal source of real-time data, particularly during an environment like this. And I'll never forget, we were at a very big, still a very big long-short equity fund, and we were talking to one of the sector heads. And the guy said, for my entire career, all I've done is pick telecom stocks. He's like, I know every company. I know the space so well. He goes, now, all of a sudden, every single day, I'm going to pick telecom stocks. And I'm like, me and my team are in a conference room on a whiteboard trying to handicap the probability of whether or not Greece is going to default. And he's like, that's just not what we do. And that kind of kicked off the thought that, wow, these guys, for any number of legitimate reasons, were dealing with risk factors, not just compensated risk factors, but also business risk factors. And this was something I credit actually, Mark Hurl, one of the guys who was in business development. He said, don't forget, these guys are running business. So you get into the back half of the year, if you're already down X percent, there's a very good reason to just go to cash. You've got a mortgage to pay. You've got analysts to pay. There's all these non... We ended up calling these uncompensated risk factors associated with any active manager, but in particular, LP funds that investors are essentially funding or exposing themselves to knowingly or unknowingly. Some investors would say, I don't believe that that's meaningful. Other investors would say, yeah, but that's the price we pay. And so we were observing that real time. Kind of an interesting corollary there is we were getting... So this big hospital foundation, which at that point, I think was certainly our largest client, if not our only client, they had SMAs with a lot of their other long-term equity funds. And so they were big enough that even the marquee names would give them separately managed accounts. And what was interesting there was not only did they have daily liquidity, which they insisted on, but they also had intramonth transparency. And so there's a lot of... And so they had a lot of... And so there's a lot of... And so there's this whole game around... And Fung and Shea talk about this a little bit in some of their early academic literature. And again, we observed it real time, but there's this whole game around reporting returns intramonth. And there's, if nothing else, just as a price discovery mechanism, the clone portfolio had a lot of value because these guys would call us, the hospital foundation would call us and say, hey, where's the clone month to date in October, for example? And I'd say, it's down however many basis points. And they'd call back in November during the rebate. And they'd say, hey, where's the clone month to date in October, for example? And I'd say, hey, where's the clone month to date in October, for example? If I'm getting my... If I'm remembering correctly, and they'd say, what's the clone portfolio up? I'd go back and say, all right, we rebalanced into... From out of these factors into these factors, the clone is up 300 basis points. And he's like, okay, so the clone made it all back. And I said, yeah. And meanwhile, he's like, all right, well, none of these... All these managers took risk off and missed the rebound. And so that was clearly the factor that the clone, for better or for worse, was insulated against. And the subject of the 24, 14 paper argued that that factor, that interim month, when you get out... The factor I'm defining here or attempting to define is when you get outside the timeframe, specifically within, call it an interim month timeframe, where on average, the long-term equity managers don't add value from rebalancing or managing the net exposure. By insulating yourself from that, sticking to your guns, for lack of a better phrase, in a systematic clone portfolio, you're effectively not paying that tax. And it is a tax over time, and that was the point of the 2014 paper was, to your exact point, we did this debrief in Q1 of 2012 and said, all right, I'm glad that we outperformed the benchmarks by 800 basis points, but was it for the right reason? Is there a risk here that we're missing? Could it go against us? And the net effect of this deep dive was the risk factor that we, by design, don't have exposure to, is this kind of what I'm going to call intramonth or higher frequency risk on, risk off, tactical management that the long-term equity managers just collectively don't add value. And in fact, actually, it's even further than that. They collectively detract value. And the thesis, just to wrap it up, the thesis of that 2014 paper, we attempted to quantify it, but the thesis of that 2014 paper was, there's reasons for this. There's these business reasons. And that was one of the benefits I credit the fund to funds experience was just simply having access to these guys. Even if it wasn't me, the partners were all senior guys. They knew the PMs of these funds. They knew the PMs of these funds. They knew the PMs of these funds. They knew the funds. One example, and I remember they said, when John Paulson's fund blew up in a good way, when he made that big short subprime trade in 2007, they were kind of laughing. We went in his office to do a manager due diligence thing. And I remember one of the proprietor, one of the founders of my fund came out. He's like, yeah. He goes, I remember when that guy was only $200 million in a merger ARB fund, which is when they first made their investment. He's like, he goes, I appreciate he made a lot of money in the short subprime trade. He's like, that looks a lot different than merger ARB, doesn't it? And he's like, you're the quant, you tell me. And I was like, yeah. A little bit of a departure. But anyway, to finally wrap this up and not belabor the point, that was an important kind of anecdotes that we were getting as the fund of funds was, we were hearing these guys like at this huge long-term equity funds, actively tell us that they were kind of outside their, out over their skis and trying to navigate this kind of risk on risk off environment that was typical during 2011.
